```

# Testing

Failing test has been added in this PR.

# Risk

Low, as the change is very simple and obvious when you look at `ReadOnlySequence<T>` ctor that accepts `ReadOnlyMemory<T>` (notice line 133 versus lines 140 and 148):

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/0d40b482e6b6c232131dc808182d6b32d9d37394/src/System.Memory/src/System/Buffers/ReadOnlySequence.cs#L130-L149

Moreover, the changed code gets triggered only when creating a `ReadOnlySequence` from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by a `MemoryManager`. All other use cases (including creating from an array or from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by an array or a string) are unaffected. And the changes are identical to those in the other backports.

# Regression

This is not a regression.

Consider the following case:
```cs
int[] arr = [1, 2, 3];
M(arr); // CS1503 here

void M(List<int> ints)
{
}
```
Since there is no implicit conversion from `int[]` to `List<int>` this code produces `CS1503` error. This can be quickly fixed the following way:
```cs
int[] arr = [1, 2, 3];
M([.. arr]);

void M(List<int> ints)
{
}
```
So I think it makes sense to suggest this as a codefix for the given error. The fix should be available on C# 12 and above and if user didn't explicitly specified they don't prefer collection expressions via an [editorconfig rule](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/fundamentals/code-analysis/style-rules/ide0300#dotnet_style_prefer_collection_expression)

Today an analyzer that wants to analyze syntax nodes needs to call `RegisterSyntaxNodeAction(callback, SyntaxKind.xxx)`.  The registered callback will then be called on every node with that kind in a particular file.

However, analyzers then need to often check if their particular options would disable their processing for a particular file.  Given that there may be a large number of nodes of a particular kind in a file, this means calling back both on all those nodes, and then having all those nodes have to check the same option over and over again to see if it's disabled.

It would be good if we could avoid all that work by giving analyzers a point to first check if they are disabled for a particular file.  We can accomplish that with a pattern we have for the other types of actions:

```c#
public abstract class AnalysisContext
{
+     public abstract void RegisterSyntaxNodeStartAction(Action<SyntaxNodeStartAnalysisContext> action);
}

+public abstract class SyntaxNodeStartAnalysisContext
+{
+    public SyntaxTree SyntaxTree { get; }
+    public Compilation Compilation { get; }
+    public AnalyzerOptions Options { get; }
+    public CancellationToken CancellationToken { get; }

+    public void RegisterSyntaxNodeAction(Action<SyntaxNodeAnalysisContext> action, params TLanguageKindEnum[] syntaxKinds);
+    public abstract void RegisterSyntaxNodeAction(Action<SyntaxNodeAnalysisContext> action, ImmutableArray<TLanguageKindEnum> syntaxKinds);
+}

public abstract class CompilationStartAnalysisContext
{
+     public abstract void RegisterSyntaxNodeStartAction(Action<SyntaxNodeStartAnalysisContext> action);
}
``` 

This would then be used by our own analyzers like so:

```c#
    protected override void InitializeWorker(AnalysisContext context)
        => context.RegisterSyntaxNodeStartAction(context =>
        {
            var option = context.GetCSharpAnalyzerOptions().FeatureXXXOption;
            if (ShouldSkipAnalysis(context, option))
                return;

             context.RegisterSyntaxNodeAction(ProcessSyntaxNode, SyntaxKind.xxx);
        });

// Or, also commonly:

    protected override void InitializeWorker(AnalysisContext context)
        => context.RegisterCompilationStartAction(context =>
        {
            // Feature not available before C#8
            if (context.Compilation.LanguageVersion() < LanguageVersion.CSharp8)
                return;

            context.RegisterSyntaxNodeStartAction(context =>
            {
                var option = context.GetCSharpAnalyzerOptions().FeatureXXXOption;
                if (ShouldSkipAnalysis(context, option))
                    return;

                 context.RegisterSyntaxNodeAction(ProcessSyntaxNode, SyntaxKind.xxx);
             });
        });
```

With this, we'll now only get the syntax node callbacks for files that we should actually be scanning.

Note: such a pattern is so common we might consider an extension (or IDE level method) to do allow you to write:

```c#
    protected override void InitializeWorker(AnalysisContext context)
        => context.RegisterSyntaxNodeAction(
            minLanguageVersion: LanguageVersion.CSharp8,
            analyzerOptions => analyzerOptions.FeatureXXXOption,
            ProcessSyntaxNode,
            SyntaxKind.Etcs);
--

This would now be the optimal way to register a feature to work on nodes, while knowing it would have virtually no runtime impact if hte langversion were too low, or if the file was excluded from analysis.

--

Note: from talking to @mavasani, we think calling this `RegisterSyntaxTreeStartAction` or `RegisterSemanticModelStartAction` may be more appropriate.  I'm fine either way.

